07382nam a22011895i 9783839451663DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97838394516637 a10.1515/97838394516632doi  a(DE-B1597)544757  a(OCoLC)1163878150  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0540002bisacsh00aPractices of Comparing :bTowards a New Understanding of a Fundamental Human Practice /ced. by Angelika Epple, Johannes Grave, Walter Erhart. 1aBielefeld : bBielefeld University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (406 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tTypologies and Forms -- tPractices of Comparing -- tPreliminary Typology of Comparative Utterances -- tIncomparability -- tOdysseus, Blackbirds, and Rain Barrels -- tWhere Do Rankings Come From? -- tHistories -- tThe Weight of Comparing in Medieval England -- tThe Shifting Grounds of Comparison in the French Renaissance -- tComparison and East-West Encounter -- tJapan as the Absolute 'Other' -- t"Goût de Comparaison" -- tInventing White Beauty and Fighting Black Slavery -- tThe Politicisation of Comparisons -- tGenealogies of Modernism -- tComparing in the Digital Age -- tAuthors and Editors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aPractices of comparing shape how we perceive, organize, and change the world. Supposedly innocent, practices of comparing play a decisive role in forming categories, boundaries, and hierarchies; but they can also give an impetus to question and change such structures. Like almost no other human practice, comparing pervades all social, political, economic, and cultural spheres. This volume outlines the program of a new research agenda that places comparative practices at the center of an interdisciplinary exploration. Its contributions combine case studies with overarching systematic considerations. They show what insights can be gained and which further questions arise when one makes a seemingly trivial practice - comparing - the subject of in-depth research.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG) (SFB 1288)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDigital humanities. 0aLiterature. 0aPolitical sociology. 4aBielefeld University Press. 4aComparing. 4aComparison. 4aCultural History. 4aDigital Humanities. 4aHistorical Change. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aPolitical Sociology. 4aSociety. 4aSociology of Knowledge. 4aTheory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aBielefeld University Press.  aComparing.  aComparison.  aCultural History.  aDigital Humanities.  aHistorical Change.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aPolitical Sociology.  aSociety.  aSociology of Knowledge.  aTheory.1 aEpple, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpple, Angelika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErhart, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErhart, Walter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrisch, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrave, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeyder, Joris Corin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHochkirchen, Britta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongxi, Zhang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLozerand, Emmanuel, econtribu